  "summary": "Hercule Poirot shows Maud Williams four photographs published in the *Sunday Comet* the week before Mrs. McKinty was murdered. Miss Williams recognizes a cloche hat worn by Janice Coltrane and finds a child in the photos familiar. During their discussion, Miss Williams suggests that Eve Kene, who would be approximately the same age as Mrs. Upwood, might be involved or targeted by someone motivated by hatred. The conversation briefly touches upon the famous Craig case.\n\nLater, Mrs. Oliver attends a play with Robin Upward. While Robin is social and enjoys the subsequent after-party, Mrs. Oliver finds the social interaction difficult. During the party, an actor named Michael discusses Robin's mother, noting her tendency to manipulate people, specifically citing her treatment of Alex Rosskov. After the event, Robin drives Mrs. Oliver back to Wisteria Manor. Upon entering the dark house, Mrs. Oliver discovers Mrs. Upwood's body in the living room. She runs to the entrance hall to inform a returning Robin that Mrs. Upwood has been murdered.\n\nInspector Spence arrives at the scene to observe the crime. He notes that the murder was \"neat and clean,\" explaining that Mrs. Upwood was strangled with her own scarf. He describes the method as an efficient constriction of the carotid artery that prevents the victim from struggling or crying out.",
